(629, 'Art', 'Sterritt', 'Art Sterritt, who also goes by the name Myanxa, trained as a carver and printmaker at \'Ksan, a historical village, museum, and art school that opened in 1970 near the former nineteenth-century village of Gitanmaax. Art attended \'Ksan from 1970 to 1972, and learned carving, as well as jewellery engraving, from established Gitxsan artists Walter Harris and Earl Muldoe. Art resides in Prince Rupert, BC, and is still active as a maker of ceremonial headdresses and totem poles for the Gitxsan and Wet\'suwet\'en peoples. (Lattimer Gallery website)', '', '', ''),
(631, 'Erwin', 'Wurm', '\"Austrian-born Erwin Wurm came to prominence with his One Minute Sculptures, a project that he began in the 1990s. In these works, Wurm gives written or drawn instructions to participants that indicate actions or poses to perform with everyday objects such as chairs, buckets, fruit, or knit sweaters. These sculptures are by nature temporal and ephemeral, challenging the traditional and formal qualities of the medium. By incorporating actions into the process, and utilizing photography to capture and convey the experiences, the boundaries between art, daily life, spectator and participant break down.While Wurm considers humour an important tool in his work, there is always an underlying social critique of contemporary culture, particularly in response to the Capitalist influences and resulting societal pressures that the artist sees as contrary to our internal ideals.Erwin Wurm, born in Bruck an der Mur/Styria, Austria, lives and works in Vienna and Limberg, Austria. - Vancouver Art Gallery', 'Austria', '', ''),
(632, 'Phoebe', 'Parsons', 'Phoebe Parsons studied at Emily Carr University of Art and Design in Vancouver where she completed her Bachelor\'s degree in Media Art with a focus in traditional film and animation studies.Parsons’ thesis video work The Fantastic Adventures of Cloudman has been screened internationally at the Vimeo Film Festival, New York, USA, and Anti Design Festival, London, UK in 2010.The artist also works as an assistant costume designer in film and television, and continues to direct and produce films.', 'Canada', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=632&ImageId=1709', 'https://www.vimeo.com/phoebeparsons'),
(633, 'Birthe', 'Piontek', 'Born and raised in Germany, Birthe moved to Canada in 2005 after receiving her MFA from the Folkwang University of the Arts in Essen, Germany. Her work has been exhibited internationally, in both solo and group shows, and is featured in many private and public collections such as the Museum of Contemporary Photography in Chicago and the Museum of Applied Arts in Gera, Germany.Birthe\'s project The Idea of North won the Critical Mass Book Award 2009, and was published as a monograph in 2011. Her most recent work, Abendlied, received the Edward Burtynsky Grant in 2018 and was published in April 2019.Birthe is an Assistant Professor of Photography in the Audain Faculty of Art at Emily Carr University of Art and Design in Vancouver and a member of the Cake Collective.', 'Canada', '', 'https://www.birthepiontek.com'),
(634, 'Jack', 'Kenna', 'Jack Kenna completed his bachelor of fine arts from Emily Carr University of Art + Design in 2019. Kenna’s practice includes painting, drawing, sculpture, and writing, and is rooted in a DIY ethos that emphasizes humour and community building.In 2018, the artist co-founded Ground Floor Art Centre, agallery and studio created to provide more opportunities fo remerging artists to exhibit, curate, perform, and gather in Vancouver. He is a 2020 &amp; 2021 Artist in Residence with the Vancouver School Board where he facilitates long-term art projects with elementary students.', 'Canada', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=634&ImageId=1697', ''),
(635, 'Sunny', 'Nestler', 'Sunny Nestler’s visual art practice is rooted in drawing and studies mechanisms of biological life using a process that mimics DNA replication and mutation. They also work in bookmaking, installation, mixed media, performance, and painting. Their subject matter cross pollinates biological processes, DIY communities, and unusual landscapes with the political affect of relatedness and adaptation. Nestler holds an MFA from Emily Carr University, where they currently teach drawing and natural science classes. Nestler has published work as an illustrator and artist’s book maker, and exhibited and performed throughout North America.', 'Canada', '', ''),
(636, 'Nicole Kelly', 'Westman', 'Nicole Kelly Westman is a visual artist of Métis and Icelandic descent that recognizes with an indebted gratitude the artists that came before her and strenuously forged space, the curators that place care at the fore of their labour, the communities that foster confidence in her practice, and the institutions and organizations that implement policies prefacing relations of trust. As an artist she enjoys practices of listening, watching, hosting, poeticizing, foraging, and sharing. Westman was previously the director of Stride Art Gallery, holds a BFA from Emily Carr University (2012),  and is currently rolling through regions like a tumbleweed. Her writing has been published in C Magazine, Inuit Art Quarterly, Instudio Magazine, and Luma Quarterly.', 'Canada', '', ''),
(637, 'Yeonoo', 'Park', 'Yeonoo Park is completing her BFA at Emily Carr University of Art + Design with a focus in painting. Her practice also involves drawing, writing, and sculpture, all contributing to reconsider everyday moments and movements.', '', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=637&ImageId=1733', ''),
(638, 'Hazel', 'Meyer', 'Hazel Meyer works with installation, performance, and text to investigate the relationships between sexuality, feminism, and material culture. Her work aims to recover the queer aesthetics, politics, and bodies often effaced within histories of infrastructure, athletics and illness. Drawing on archival research, she designs immersive installations that bring various troublemakers—lesbians-feminists, gender outlaws, leather-dykes—into a performative space that centres desire, queerness, and sweat.Hazel presently lives in Vancouver, on the unceded traditional territories of the xʷməθkwəy̓əm, Skwxwú7mesh and Səl̓ílwətaɬ Nations with her frequent collaborator and partner Cait McKinney and dog Regie.', 'Canada', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=638&ImageId=1734', 'https://www.hazelmeyer.com'),
(639, 'Jaclyn (Jackie)', 'Dives', 'Jackie Dives explores themes of identity, gender, and mental health in her art practice, which is primarily . photography-based.', 'Canada', '', ''),
(640, 'Sharona', 'Franklin', 'Sharona Franklin is a multidisciplinary artist, writer and advocate. Her work explores radical thera&shy;pies, cybernetic craft, ecological systems, bio-ritualism, pharmacological and social inter-depen&shy;dency disseminating mythologies of class and biocitizenship within disability.  Franklin&rsquo;s visual media practice can be viewed through social media platforms:   \\t@paid.technologies \\t@star_seeded \\t@hot.crip   Through ontological study and utilizing natural, salvaged, biodegradable, edible, print media and digital mediums, her psychedelic works invite the viewer into facets of biophar&shy;maceutical investigations and educational community practice.', 'Canada', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=640&ImageId=1869', ''),
(641, 'Marisa', 'Kriangwiwat Holmes', 'Marisa Kriangwiwat Holmes is a Hong Kong born, Vancouver-based artist who graduated from Emily Carr University with a major in Photography and minor in Curatorial Practices.Recent exhibitions include Open Heart, Run Off, Sibling Gallery Toronto, and Green Glass Door, Trapp Projects, Vancouver.', 'Canada', '', 'https://www.marisakriangwiwatholmes.com/'),
(642, 'Jag', 'Nagra', 'Jag Nagra is a queer South Asian artist passionate about community development and ending the stigma against LGBTQ+ people within the South Asian community. Nagra has over 14 years of experience as a Graphic Designer and over 8 years as a professional Illustrator. She is currently serving as Creative Director on the board of Vancouver’s Punjabi Market Regeneration Collective.', 'Canada', '', 'https://Jagnagra.com'),
(643, 'Vicky', 'Alexander', '', '', '', ''),
(645, 'Wen Wen', 'Lu', 'Wen Wen (Cherry) Lu is a multimedia artist interested in exploring the hidden, the small and the forgotten through installation, illustration and animation. Taking inspiration from family history, she seeks to combine it with the present experiences of culture, nature and community to create something that questions. Her work has been shown in spaces such as Richmond Nature Park, International Arts Gallery, Centre A, Concourse Art Gallery, New Westminster Museum and Gallery, Access Gallery, and Burnaby Art Gallery.', 'Canada', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=645&ImageId=1753', 'http://www.wenwenart.com/'),
(646, 'Randy Lee', 'Cutler', 'Randy Lee Cutler is an interdisciplinary artist whose practice weaves together themes of collaboration, materiality, science and fiction. Working with printed matter, collage, video, and performance, she has exhibited at the Biennale of Sydney NIRIN 2020, Belkin Art Gallery and Vancouver Art Gallery among others. She recently published An Elemental Typology, an artist book exploring the cultural configurations of minerals in philosophy, mining, science and spirituality. Randy is a Professor at Emily Carr University.', 'Canada', '', ''),
(647, 'Henri', 'Robideau', 'Henri Robideau is a photographer and cultural narrator whose practice is grounded in history and animated by the events of our times. His lifelong involvement in photography incorporates more than fifty years of teaching, professional production for many of Canada’s leading artists and personal art creation incorporating photographic imagery and handwritten narrative text.Born 1946 in Bristol, Connecticut, he grew up in New England, North Carolina and California, where his teen years were spent in the booming post WWII suburbs of San Diego county. In university he studied chemistry at San Diego State College for two years but dropped out and moved in 1966 to the Bay Area, pursuing a life in the arts. He trained as a commercial photographer at Laney College in Oakland, before emigrating to Vancouver in 1970 as a refugee from the violence of America and as the fulfillment of a promise to his grandfather to someday return to the land of his ancestors.His first Canadian job as photo-technician for the Vancouver Public Library Historical Photograph Section, provided an immersion into Vancouver’s visual history and introduced him to the work of photographer Mattie Gunterman. In 1976 he left the world of archives and researched Mattie Gunterman’s life, producing an exhibition of her work that toured 26 venues and led to the 1995 publication of her historical biography, Flapjacks &amp; Photographs.In 1980 he launched a decade-long project The Pancanadienne Gianthropological Survey, crisscrossing Canada in search of monumental human activity and the true meaning of Canada. After producing a series of sixty large scale black and white panoramic photographs he moved to Montreal in 1987 to work on the eastern side of the Survey. On July 14, his second day in Montreal, his panoramas were destroyed in a flood. His lost work was later celebrated in the publication Canada’s Gigantic! Four years in Montreal came to an end with attending the events at Oka, followed by a trip to Japan he’d been putting off since he was 9. The Pancanadienne Gianthropological Survey went largely unfinished after amassing more than 1500 panoramas, but out of it came 500 Fun Years a narrative on Colonialism done for the 1992 500th anniversary of resistance.In 1991 he moved back to Vancouver working for Green Peace photographer Robert Keziere out of Jack Shadbolt’s old studio on Cambie Street providing photographic services and productions for Canada’s leading artists, galleries and publications. He also taught photography at Emily Carr College of Art as a sessional for the next 25 years. For the past thirty years his practice has been in the form of multi panel photographic montages with holographic text. Sometimes this work is an introspective reflection on the ironic tragedy of human existence, as is the case with the two series The Crossroads Of Life and Acts Of God. Other times history and politics provide the narrative as in the millennial snapshot, Four Directions of the Okanagan, and most recently the anecdotal account of 40 years of Vancouver development, Eraser Street.Henri Robideau’s photography has been exhibited and collected both in Canada and internationally. He lives and works in Vancouver respectfully on the unceded ancestral territory of the Musqueam, Squamish and Tsleil-Waututh Peoples.', 'Canada', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=647&ImageId=1775', 'https://henrirobideau.ca'),
(648, 'Laurie M', 'Landry', 'Laurie M Landry attended Wells’ Island Mountain School for the Arts in the late 1970s, and completed the Emily Carr University of Art &amp; Design’s Fine Arts Techniques program in 2008. She has since continued training with mentor programs and in-class workshops, including Studio Escalier in Paris, France, and Toni Onley Artist Project, Wells, Canada. Laurie lives and work in Vancouver, BC.', 'Canada', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=648&ImageId=1796', 'https://www.laurielandry.com'),
(649, 'Dejan', 'Radovanovic', 'Dejan Radovanovic is a Yugoslavian born, Vancouver based media artist working in film, video, animation and sound. His work has been screened internationally on exhibitions and festivals such as New York City Independent Film Festival (New York, US), Distant Nature (Knoll Galerie, Vienna, Austria), Creative Tech Week (New York, US), Generative Gallery (Moscow, Russia), MADATAC (Madrid, Spain), and the Psychedelic Film and Music Festival (New York, US), among others.Dejan spent nine years as Art Director and Production Designer in Film and Television Production before founding his Studio in 2004.', 'Canada', '', ''),
(650, 'Rina', 'Lyshaug', 'Rina Lyshaug is a Norwegian-Sámi intermedia installation artist who investigates paradigms in visual culture and creates installations comprised of photography, video, and sculpture that collectively refute expectations of image readability. She holds a BFA with a major in Film, Video and Integrated Media from Emily Carr University of Art + Design and a fine arts diploma from Breivang Kunstskole in Tromsø, Norway. Her work has exhibited in The Lind Prize 2020 Exhibition at the Polygon Gallery, and The Reorganized Organ at Vivo Media Arts Centre (2017). She received the Emily Carr University of Art + Design Media Award for Concept Development + Academic Rigour in 2019 for her work, what would that be like? (the thing onto itself), was shortlisted for the Lind Prize in 2020.', 'Canada', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=650&ImageId=1840', 'https://rinalyshaug.com'),
(651, 'Shion Skye', 'Carter', 'Shion Skye Carter is a Japanese-Canadian dance artist. Through choreography hybridized with calligraphy, video, sculpture, and sound, her work celebrates the discovery of one&rsquo;s ethnographic identity and connection to heritage.  She is co-founder of the interdisciplinary duo olive theory with musician Stefan Nazarevich, where they experiment at the intersection between embodied performance, installation, and live sound.  Carter has performed across Canada and worked as Artist-in-Residence at What Lab and Left of Main in Vancouver, as well as LE&Ntilde;A Artist Residency on Galiano Island.', 'Canada', '', 'https://shionskyecarter.com'),
(652, 'Ryley', 'O\'Byrne', 'Ryley O&rsquo;Byrne uses text, image, clothing, ceramics, and film to examine and explore relational dynamics, intimacy, and the process of meaning-making.  She attended the Mountain School of Art in Los Angeles, and was a resident of the Critical Art Writing Ensemble III at the Banff Centre.  Her work has been exhibited internationally and she has texts in or forthcoming in publications including Canadian Art, Room Journal, Public Parking, and The Capilano Review.', 'Canada', '', 'https://www.ryleyd.com'),
(653, 'Gerri', 'York', 'Gerri York&rsquo;s practice focuses on the material, magical and spectral aspects of photography. Her recent work Fold, exploring the nature of camera-less photography, was shown at Malaspina Printmakers&#39; as part of Capture Photography Festival in 2019.  York&rsquo;s work has been exhibited in a wide variety of exhibitions and juried shows, and is included in both public and private collections in Canada and internationally.', 'Canada', '', ''),
(654, 'Osvaldo Ramirez', 'Castillo', 'Originally from El Salvador, Osvaldo Ramirez Castillo has exhibited extensively across Canada and internationally in spaces such as the Southern Alberta Art Gallery, the International Print Center in New York, MAI (Montr&eacute;al Arts interculturels), La Halle Saint Pierre in Paris, and at Marte- Museo de Arte de El Salvador among others.  He is a recipient of the Artist Studio Award Program from the City of Vancouver (2015-2018), a Pollock-Krasner Foundation Grant (2010), and numerous others from the Canada Arts Council.', 'Canada', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=654&ImageId=1847', 'https://www.osvaldoramirezcastillo.com'),
(655, '', 'Kisyuu', 'Kisyuu was born and raised in Japan and was given a calligraphy master name &ldquo;Kisyuu&rdquo; from her master Kosyuu Kobayashi at the age of 18. She has earned numerous awards, and since moving to Canada in 2007 has been working on her calligraphy installations, workshops, lessons, exhibitions, live performances, and commissioned artworks.  Kisyuu writes both traditional and modern freestyle calligraphy, using the brush and sumi ink to express her true self, and wishing to create both inner and outer peace.', 'Canada', '', 'http://www.kisyuu-calligraphy.com/'),
(656, 'Wade', 'Comer', 'Wade Comer has been a photographer for nearly thirty years. His work investigates two main concepts: how we see, and humanity&rsquo;s effect on our environment.  The camera is Comer&rsquo;s primary form of expression. Whether using the camera to create abstract representations of landscape, or to highlight our human existence by documenting what we leave behind, his projects explore the theme of human impact on the environment, the contrasts of urban existence with nature, and the memory of the individual versus the group.', 'Canada', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=656&ImageId=1851', 'http://www.wadecomer.com'),
(657, 'Fred', 'Wah', 'Fred Wah is a Vancouver poet who has published numerous books of poetry, fiction, and criticism. His work has been awarded the Governor-General&rsquo;s Award, among others. He is a former Parliamentary Poet Laureate and an Officer of the Order of Canada.  His best-known book is Diamond Grill (1996), a biofiction about a small-town Chinese-Canadian caf&eacute;. He collaborated with poet Rita Wong on beholden: a poem as long as the river (2019) and Talonbooks has published Music at the Heart of Thinking (2020).', 'Canada', '', 'http://www.fredwah.ca'),
(658, 'Nick', 'Conbere', 'Nick Conbere is an artist who presents landscapes based on experiential interpretations of place and investigates the intertwining of natural and human-made environments.  He has exhibited at the Minneapolis Institute of Arts, International Print Center and Touchstones Nelson Museum of Art and History, and his illustrations have been featured in the New York Times and other publications.  He works as an Associate Professor at Emily Carr University of Art and Design.', 'Canada', '', 'http://www.nickconbere.com'),
(659, '', 'Tafui', 'Tafui was born in Jamaica and is a multidisciplinary artist and designer who works in paintings, printmaking, wood carving, and textile art. She received a DEC in Studio Art from Dawson College and a BFA in design from Concordia University.  Tafui is known for her modern, bold black-and-white patterns that adorn her textiles and art prints, and her work can be found in various public art collections such as the Bank of Jamaica and the City of Ottawa.', 'Canada', '', 'https://shoptafui.com'),
(660, 'Kathleen', 'Ritter', 'Kathleen Ritter is a Canadian artist based in Vancouver and Paris. Her works takes an investigative approach to specific histories, institutions, and constructs of power, gender, language and technology. Through a process of resuscitation and recontextualization of archival images, recorded media, and text, she draws connections between disparate fields, uncovering material from the past as a potential cipher for the present. She was a resident at La Cit&eacute; Internationale des Arts, Paris, in 2014. Exhibitions have taken place at Mus&eacute;e d&rsquo;art contemporain de Montr&eacute;al; Open Studio and G Gallery, Toronto; and Battat Contemporary, Montr&eacute;al. Her writing on contemporary art has appeared in ESSE, Prefix Photo, Fillip and The Brooklyn Rail as well as in numerous catalogues.', 'Canada', '', ''),
(661, 'Mustaali', 'Raj', 'Mustaali Raj is an independent visual artist, art director, and graphic designer whose work lies at an intersection between interdisciplinary concept development and visual communication.  As an engineer turned designer, his creative process is a cohesive blend between left and right brain thinking. He is a circle, living in a square, drawing triangles.', 'Canada', '', 'https://mustaaliraj.com'),
(662, 'Paige', 'Gratland', 'Paige Gratland is a visual artist and filmmaker working in documentary, craft, and print publication. Her conceptual practice disrupts dominant narratives, reworking material culture for queer audiences.  In 2019 she learned to weave at the Richmond Weavers and Spinners Guild, and recently completed Master Weavers Level One at Olds College, AB. Her woven work is informed by relational colour theory and explores the link between specific colourways and historical memory.  Employing creative strategies to seek out intergenerational community and make connections is a theme that runs through her practice.', 'Canada', '', 'https://www.instagram.com/pgratland/'),
(663, '', 'Theatre Replacement', 'Theatre Replacement is an ongoing collaboration between James Long and Maiko Yamamoto. Whether working together or apart, the pair work with a wide range of collaborators and use extended processes to create performances, events and public art projects from intentionally simple beginnings. Their work is about a genuine attempt to coexist. Conversations, interviews and arguments collide with Yamamoto and Long&rsquo;s aesthetics, resulting in theatrical experiences that are authentic, immediate and hopeful. The company continues to build and tour work, and has been presented at internationally recognized festivals and venues including Festival TransAm&eacute;riques (Montr&eacute;al), Fusebox Festival (Austin, TX), Noorderzon Festival (Groningen, NL), Dublin Theatre Festival (Ireland), Soho Rep. (New York), artsdepot (London) and Meteor Festival (Norway). In 2019, Yamamoto and Long were the first co-recipients of the Siminovitch Prize in Directing, Canada&rsquo;s largest prize in recognition of innovation and excellence in theatre.', 'Canada', '', 'https://theatrereplacement.org');
