(158, 'Jubilee Fountain', '', 'Memorial or monument', 'In place', 'Lost Lagoon', 'Stanley Park', '', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/4462d36c6a4dad5a59bb8807dace6fdd', 'City of Vancouver', 'Stanley Park', 'NE corner of Lost Lagoon', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.138349, 49.295666]}', 'This fountain has a Heritage Monument designation. It was installed to celebrate Vancouver\'s 50th birthday - the Golden Jubilee - in 1936.', 227, 1936),
(161, 'Terry Fox Memorial', 'The miracle of Terry Fox was that he was an ordinary young man who turned his response to pain and loss into a triumph of hope and courage. When Terry lost his right leg to cancer in 1977 he decided to raise funds for cancer research. He would run across Canada and ask every Canadian to join the fight against cancer by donating one dollar. He began his Marathon of Hope in Newfoundland on April 12, 1980 heading for the Pacific and home 5,300 miles away. As he ran his daily 26 miles, the lone figure with the distinctive hop-and-skip gait became a symbol that captured the imagination of a nation.  On September 2, Terry was forced to abandon his run when cancer was discovered in his lung. That morning he had written 3,318 miles under the date in his diary. But the Marathon of Hope was not over. Messages of affection and encouragement flooded in and donations to continue the battle against cancer, eventually totaled more than $30 million. In the last year of his brief life Terry received many honours, but Terry Fox will always be remembered most as the young man who demonstrated and took a nation along with him on his Marathon of Hope. Dedicated 1984 by the people of British Columbia; Architect:Franklin Allen / The Corner Group; Illustration: Ian Bateson\"', 'Other', 'Removed', 'BC Place Stadium (Downtown)', '855 Beatty Street at Robson (Downtown)', 'brick, tile, concrete, stainless steel, Plexiglas', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/d05d6c53d878025f245422566257fa81', 'Province of British Columbia', '', 'entrance to BC Place Stadium, W. side of Terry Fox Plaza', '', 'This four-sided architectural memorial sits on a raised platform of concrete and tiles outside BC Place. According to the pamphlet Downtown Vancouver Architecture and Public Art (1998), \"the memorial is a postmodern interpretation of the triumphal arches of Rome.\" There is a stylized cast lion on each corner of the roof. The square pavilion houses a map of Canada and  an image of one-legged runner Terry Fox by Ian Bateson etched into polished steel surfaces. The inscriptions commemorate Fox\'s heroic effort to run across Canada to raise funds for cancer research.  The \"Marathon of Hope\" eventually raised over $30m.', 8, 1984),
(163, 'Joe Fortes Drinking Fountain', 'Joe Fortes was born in Barbados and jumped ship to stay  in Vancouver in 1885. He made it his mission to teach people to swim and taught hundreds of children and adults.According to the Vancouver Sun (April 7, 2001, H4) Fortes owned only one book: The Imitation of Christ by Thomas a Kempis. His funeral in 1922 was the biggest in Vancouver history.', 'Memorial or monument', 'In place', 'Alexandra Park', '1600 block of Beach Avenue', 'Bronze, granite', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/85c72dc2d0c8e3e59a892bd537abc9f3', 'City of Vancouver', 'West End', 'South side of Alexander Park, facing Beach Avenue between Bidwell and Denman Street', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.142386, 49.285563]}', 'A heritage monument, this  granite water fountain has a carved text and  inset bronze relief plaque that commemorates the first  lifeguard at this beach.', 98, 1927),
(165, 'Marker of Change', 'It took nearly eight years for this monument to come into being. A committee was formed in conjunction with Capilano College and a subsequent national competition drew 98 entries. Toronto artist Beth Alber won with the design incorporating 14 pink granite benches in a circle.  It stands as a reminder of violence against women in society.  The competition policies state that, \"The Women\'s Monument is conceived as a rational monument to be located in Vancouver, BC, dedicated to all women who have been murdered by men, and naming the 14 women killed in Montreal on Dec 6,1989. It will provide a focus for healing and a tangible symbol of remembrance.\" Beth Alber\'s artist proposal states,  \"The circle, the symbol used by women for centuries to represent a continuum, in a non-hierarchical way, is one of the major elements for this Women\'s Monument. It is a symbol of women\'s spirit and is associated with the idea of a protected or consecrated space.\"  During the course of the project, considerable controversy was stirred up by the wording of the inscription which is dedicated to \"all women who have been murdered by men\".  Many people felt this inscription was too political. Some were critical about the eventual cost of the monument, approximately $500,000, which they felt could have been put to better purpose.  Many felt that the monument was too specific and was inappropriately sited in a public place, and that public money shouldn\'t be used to commemorate what was construed to be a private grief. But despite the obstacles, \"Marker of Change\" was unveiled in Thornton Park on December 6th, 1997 exactly eight years after the 14 women were killed.', 'Site-integrated work', 'In place', 'Thornton Park', 'Main Street & Terminal', 'Pink granite', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/f055679e2b17749c3364a2c16a4fe891', '', 'Strathcona', 'Central area in front of the bus terminal', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.099, 49.27401]}', 'The monument consists of a 100\' diameter circle of 14 pink granite benches each 5.5\' long with a slight bowl in the top.  Each bench is inscribed with the name of one of the 14 women killed by a gunman on December 6th, 1989, at the l\'Ecole Polytechnique, University of Montreal.  The benches are about the length and width of a woman\'s body and the depression in the center of each bench catches rain water, a reference to tears. A 98\' diameter circle outside the benches is set w/ 500 7½\" square tiles with the names of donors. The circle is situated close to the center of the park and makes reference to ancient stone circles. The space inside the circle is slightly domed and covered with grass. An alter-like podium stands just outside the circles and bears the name of the piece and an inscription. Over time, Marker of Change has quietly asserted itself into the consciousness of the community and has become a site for individual reflection and meditation as well as a place of discovery.', 212, 1997),
