(168, 'Whaling Wall VIII', 'The piece honours the Sea Shepard Society and was commissioned to aid in the education and protection of endangered animals.', 'Mural', 'Removed', 'Wyland Bldg. (Downtown)', '1190 Melville Street (Downtown)', 'Paint on concrete', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/0ad6c6bc1a72410b3298843be8f4b06c', 'private', 'Downtown', 'Exterior east wall', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.124284, 49.287533]}', 'The large mural covers the side of the building in blues and greys and features a pod of Orca Whales on the northern BC coast.', 216, 1985),
(169, 'Girl Waiting for a Bus', '', 'Sculpture', 'In place', 'Parkview Towers', 'Burrard & Cornwall Street', 'Concrete, painted white', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/8a192294173ecb8798cb537157269edd', 'private', 'Kitsilano', 'Lawn west of building front entrance', '', 'Apt\'s first sculpture, it was offered for sale to the Park Board which declined. It was purchased privately for Parkview Towers in 1962.  In 1967 it was smashed by vandals but later repaired.', 9, 1962),
(170, 'The Builders', '\"The sculpture is a tribute to the immigrants who settled in Canada.\" It was carved for the City Shapes Sculpture Symposium for Vancouver\'s centennial in 1986.', 'Sculpture', 'In place', 'Discovery Park', 'Burrard & Dunsmuir Street', 'Black Quebec granite', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/5432d9ea7e04b737a3d9739689b4f9c8', 'Province of British Columbia', 'Downtown', '', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.120121, 49.285633]}', 'A black granite sculpture made of three blocks. It is the artist\'s impression of a person in prayer using simple, strong forms.', 102, 1986),
(171, 'Vessel', '', 'Sculpture', 'In place', 'Discovery Park', 'Burrard & Dunsmuir Street', 'Granite', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/d85a3798ed34a29765068605622570e6', 'Province of British Columbia', 'Downtown', 'Right of escalators', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.120043, 49.285603]}', 'The sculpture is made of abstract geometric forms and constructed to suggest a ship. It sits on the grass outside the downtown skytrain station.', 152, 1986),
(172, 'Inukshuk', 'The welcoming figure was made on the Inuit model for the NWT pavillion designed by Bing Thom  and \"shaped like a five-story igloo\" at Expo 86.  The figure was sited at English Bay after the fair. The stones were brought in from a quarry in the Fraser Valley and then shaped and stacked by crane and pinned together with rebar. Inukshuks in the north are usually much smaller and the rocks are balanced on each other.  They act as sign posts or distance markers that can be seen on the flat horizon. Artist Kanak said,  \"By a lake an Inukshuk means lots of fish.\"  The figure is a \"reminder of the ingenuity of my people in addressing transportation and communications challenges prior to the introduction of modern technology.\" (sources: M.Farrow, V.Sun, April 24, 1985; V.Province, May 5, 1985)', 'Sculpture', 'In place', 'English Bay', 'Bidwell and shoreline walk', 'Granite boulders', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/c75ca4af54353db17ba518c3994421cb', 'City of Vancouver', 'West End', 'Shoreline walk, foot of Bidwell, E. of bathhouse', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.143704, 49.284323]}', 'Built of stacked granite blocks in a human form, Inukshuks are symbols of welcome in the north.  This one weighs 31,500 kg. It is built of gigantic rocks and stands 6 meters high.', 211, 1986),
(173, 'Fountain of the Pioneers', '\"..my fountain sculptures are an attempt to unify water--the life force of the universe that flows in an elusive cyclical course throughout eternity--with an immutable metal sculpture.\"', 'Fountain or water feature', 'In place', 'Bentall Bldg.', '500 Burrard Street', 'Bronze', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/5d33a23037b5b3f196c9dfd9d426bc55', 'private', 'Downtown', 'Front entrance of main tower', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.11782, 49.286242]}', 'Water splashes down two levels of this abstract rounded form and into the pool below. The sculpture is the centre piece of the long rectangular pool in front of the Bentall towers.', 150, 1969),
(175, 'Symbols of the Cuneiforms', '', 'Sculpture', 'In place', '', '750 Burrard Street', 'Metal, plexiglass', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/0f965866911e91600959e5aa54b04dff', 'private', 'Downtown', 'Exterior, NW corner facing Burrard', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.12202, 49.283618]}', 'This artwork is a delicate metal relief with plexiglas inserts.  The white sections are lighted at night. It is mounted on the exterior northwest corner of the building at Burrard and Robson (formerly the Vancouver Public Library). The piece was saved when the building was renovated from the old library.', 90, 1960),
