(841, 'Koco, Brewers Park, August 11, 2019', 'The public art Koco, Brewers Park, August 19, 2019 by Peter Gazendam is a single, significant sculpture orientated within the landscape architecture in a central, plaza-like location facing Stainsbury Avenue. The subject of the work is a group of women who practice “square” or “plaza” dancing in the neighbourhood. The tradition has roots in both ancient and modern Chinese history, and is a popular exercise routine performed to music in squares, plazas and parks around the world. These local performances have been a consistent scene in the otherwise rapidly changing community of Cedar Cottage. The sessions occur most mornings in the tennis courts at Brewers Park, at the Cedar Cottage Community House, or other nearby locations. The sculpture depicts one of these dancers, Koco, in six poses, each pose distinct but merging into one another, atop a square base. The sculpture was produced using 3D scanning and printing technology to capture the dancer and her movements before the final bronze form.', 'Sculpture', 'In place', '', 'Victoria Drive & Stainsbury Avenue', 'Silicon Bronze, Stainless Steel', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/abf0b2e0e4817a2876d6782e3f485ae4', 'Privately owned', '', 'On private property fronting Stainsbury Ave', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.065966, 49.252076]}', 'Koco, Brewers Park, August 11, 2019, 2020 was commissioned by Strand Development as part of their participation in the City of Vancouver\'s Public Art Program for Private Development.', 580, 2020),
(842, 'On the Other Hand', 'Randy Lee Cutler’s On the Other Hand (2020) was presented on transit shelters throughout the city from September 7 - October 4, 2020. The work, selected from an extensive collage series composed of cut-outs from National Geographic magazines, embraces the COVID virus by channelling its RNA code to cast spells through hieroglyphic forms. By bringing disparate elements together into new configurations, a lexicon of human gestures and cultural artifacts is cast open to interpretation, resonating with our shared bodily experiences of uncertainty.', 'Two-dimensional artwork', 'Removed', 'Transit shelters around the city', '', '', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/38b60e90fbf763a52108eb97fbdd270b', 'City of Vancouver', '', '20 Transit Shelter advertisement locations', '', 'Platforms 2020: Public Works is a monthly series of temporary public art projects that presented from June 2020 until the end of December 2020.These artworks were selected through an open call inviting Vancouver-based artists to share projects that they have been working on that respond to the circumstances of living during a pandemic and critical time of change.The public art program was launched on transit shelters, billboards, and video screens throughout the city.', 646, 2020),
(843, 'Frontline Workers', 'Frontline Workers exhibited on the billboard at Helmcken near Granville (September 7 to October 4, 2020).  Frontline Workers is a digital drawing based on a warrior character the artist created prior to the pandemic. During the first stages of COVID-19, Nagra re-imagined the warrior as a frontline healthcare worker battling the spread of the virus. ​​​​​It was a way for the artist to cope with overwhelming anxiety from not knowing what COVID-19 would bring during its early stages.', 'Two-dimensional artwork', 'Removed', '', '', 'Paper poster', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/22d14b3bcf660f0e045fba63a42a777b', 'Privately owned', 'Downtown', 'Impark Parking Lot on Helmcken between Granville St and Howe St', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.124837, 49.27861]}', 'Platforms 2020: Public Works is a monthly series of temporary public art projects that presented from June 2020 until the end of December 2020.These artworks were selected through an open call inviting Vancouver-based artists to share projects that they have been working on that respond to the circumstances of living during a pandemic and critical time of change.The public art program was launched on transit shelters, billboards, and video screens throughout the city.', 642, 2020),
(844, 'Blusson Wall', '', 'Two-dimensional artwork', 'In place', 'Blusson Spinal Cord Centre', '818 W 10th Ave', '', '', 'Privately owned', 'Fairview', '', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.123566, 49.261523]}', '', 643, 2019),
(845, 'Isolated', 'Isolated presented on twenty transit shelter posters throughout the city from October 5 to November 1, 2020.  Isolated are drawings by Wen Wen Lu that the artist began when isolation measures were first introduced. They became a way of exploring day-to-day changes and documenting thoughts, observations, feelings, or imaginings during the pandemic. Isolated is an expanding visual record, proving heavier as each day passed and more united as the weeks accumulated.', 'Two-dimensional artwork', 'Removed', '', '', '2D Print', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/4ad21bc32f26f1d10ddeb8d0283f66be', 'Privately owned', '', 'Twenty (20) transit shelter advertisement locations around the city', '', 'Platforms 2020: Public Works is a monthly series of temporary public art projects that presented from June 2020 until the end of December 2020.These artworks were selected through an open call inviting Vancouver-based artists to share projects that they have been working on that respond to the circumstances of living during a pandemic and critical time of change.The public art program was launched on transit shelters, billboards, and video screens throughout the city.', 645, 2020),
(847, 'The Giant Hand And The Birth of Gianthropology', 'In the grand scheme of Vancouver’s heritage, the neon period from 1925 to 1960 is perhaps the city’s most heralded example of its transition from gloomy sawmill town to vibrant metropolis. At the peak of this glowing epoch there were thousands of electrified gas filled glass tubes in the Terminal City’s neon jungle. A big hiccup in this brightlights-big-city story came with the blackouts of WWII when civil defence restrictions lead to a new category of no neon outdoor advertising known as “Spectaculars.”When McGavin’s Bakery approached Neon Products for an animated neon of Mother Hubbard’s bread, a “Spectacular” was suggested instead. A hand of enormous proportions was proposed, roughly the same size as the Statue of Liberty’s, but instead of grasping the eternal flame of freedom, Mother Hubbard’s digits would raise on high a leviathan loaf of liberty bread! Genius! McGavin’s, a big supporter of Victory Bonds, approved.Ironically, work on the Giant Hand &amp; Loaf didn’t begin until after blackout restrictions had been lifted at the end of the war. Progress slowed when McGavin’s roof required fortification supporting the added weight. Then the “Spectacular” installers were unavailable, preoccupied by a Log Cabin Cookies billboard featuring a real log cabin with smoking chimney and Mom inside whipping up maple creams. Finally in September 1948, the “Spectacular” crew convened on the roof of McGavin’s and over the next four months assembled the sheet metal loaf and concrete mixed with vermiculite hand, and a cuff hiding the steel bridgework. The finished Giant Hand &amp; Loaf stood atop McGavin’s bakery from 1949 through 1973.When Henri Robideau photographed the Giant Hand &amp; Loaf in February 1973, its cuff had blown away in a wind storm and one of its fingers had rotted off. This image became the first in his life-long photographic study of humanity’s attraction to bigness, a new science he called Gianthropology. He conducted Gianthropological Digs along the Pacific cordillera throughout the 1970’s, culminating in the 1980 exhibition Giant Things, featuring the Giant Hand &amp; Loaf as its signature image. Expanding on that huge success he launched the Pancanadienne Gianthropological Survey, portaging around Canada in the 1980’s, photographing the monumental in the form of panoramic images.', 'Two-dimensional artwork', 'In place', 'CBC Vancouver Broadcast Centre Plaza', '700 Hamilton Street', 'Digital print on vinyl', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/f396dc57ea3b3baf9855a9a67d03008a', 'Vancouver Heritage Foundation', 'Downtown', 'On the wall to the right of the main entrance of CBC Vancouver.', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.114234, 49.279663]}', 'THE WALL is a Vancouver Heritage Foundation public art initiative. It is made possible by a partnership between Vancouver Heritage Foundation and CBC Radio-Canada, and is produced in partnership with the City of Vancouver Public Art Program. THE WALL features a new artist every year.', 647, 2020),
(848, 'Pandemic Lip Reading', 'Pandemic Lip Reading (2020) presented on a billboard on Helmcken Street near Granville Street. Growing up, Landry was taught to assimilate and pass as a hearing person by relying on visual cues such as reading lips. With health measures such as personal protective equipment in place the artist can no longer accommodate the hearing world. This piece show Landry\'s difficulties navigating the pandemic as a Deaf person, and the hope that we can collectively adapt to new ways of communicating that go beyond hearing.', 'Two-dimensional artwork', 'Removed', '', '', 'Paper poster', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/5b9b09cf15c473f014c5b488b6786269', 'City of Vancouver', 'Downtown', 'Impark Parking Lot on Helmcken between Granville St and Howe St', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.124837, 49.27861]}', 'Platforms 2020: Public Works is a monthly series of temporary public art projects that presented from June 2020 until the end of December 2020.These artworks were selected through an open call inviting Vancouver-based artists to share projects that they have been working on that respond to the circumstances of living during a pandemic and critical time of change.The public art program was launched on transit shelters, billboards, and video screens throughout the city.', 648, 2020),
(849, 'Pandemik Piks', 'Pandemik Piks, a series of drawings presented on 20 digital screens throughout the city, was originally conceived on Instagram loosely around the idea of hair. Midway through the project, when the deaths of Breonna Taylor and countless others filled the news, the artist&#39;s feed was populated with black squares. In response to these ambiguous squares the artist scanned, altered, and reversed the drawings, creating exploding and flowering hair piks. The series now reflects her thoughts on the world being on fire.', 'Two-dimensional artwork', 'Removed', 'Digital Street Furniture', '', 'Digital Collages of Drawings', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/79aab2ebc8c20d265d6d26a08aa7de50', 'City of Vancouver', '', '20 locations throughout the City', '', 'Platforms 2020: Public Works is a monthly series of temporary public art projects that presented from June 2020 until the end of December 2020.These artworks were selected through an open call inviting Vancouver-based artists to share projects that they have been working on that respond to the circumstances of living during a pandemic and critical time of change.The public art program was launched on transit shelters, billboards, and video screens throughout the city.', 476, 2020),
(850, 'Coast Salish Artist', 'Coast Salish Artist, a self-portrait by the Musqueam and Coast Salish artist and carver Chrystal Sparrow, presented on twenty transit-shelter posters throughout the city from October 5 to November 1, 2020. This is a photograph of the artist adorned in Native American regalia, a reflection on famous 19th century Native American Indian portraits that presented subjects in beadwork, traditional adornments, and fabrics from that time.Sparrow explains: “I have found that adding these Native American regalia images to my self-portraits has delivered a significant connection to the idea of historical ceremonies practiced by wearing regalia. I also felt a sense of nobility, respect, and inspiration when a chief\'s regalia covered a part of my body. I also used images of salmon leather, Coast Salish formlines, berries, patterns and textures. My interest to use self-portraits has become a study of traditional art and regalia to be manifested in my work; with the intent to discover more about my Coast Salish, Cree and Shuswap art practices.\"', 'Two-dimensional artwork', 'Removed', '', '', 'Photograph', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/13a46ded135c7ac3ddb2e46392d0244a', 'Privately owned', '', 'Twenty (20) transit shelter advertisement locations around the city', '', 'Platforms 2020: Public Works is a monthly series of temporary public art projects that presented from June 2020 until the end of December 2020.  These artworks were selected through an open call inviting Vancouver-based artists to share projects that they have been working on that respond to the circumstances of living during a pandemic and critical time of change.  The public art program was launched on transit shelters, billboards, and video screens throughout the city.', 491, 2020),
(851, 'Talking Trees', 'Dejan Radovanovic\'s video Talking Trees presented on the VanLive! screen at the corner of Granville and Robson Streets (November 2 to 29, 2020). This meditative piece is a digital animation of a miracle forest where trees can communicate with their visitors, helping them to create interpretations, speculations, and meanings. Placing the inner world above external reality this video reveals that there is no better place to contemplate ourselves than in the woods.', 'Media work', 'In place', 'Robson/Granville Screens', '', '', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/e771a8aa13f731ff6313c8d1a8c8b2ee', 'City of Vancouver', 'Downtown', 'north-east corner of the Robson and Granville intersection', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.119628, 49.281344]}', 'Platforms 2020: Public Works is a monthly series of temporary public art projects that presented from June 2020 until the end of December 2020.These artworks were selected through an open call inviting Vancouver-based artists to share projects that they have been working on that respond to the circumstances of living during a pandemic and critical time of change.The public art program was launched on transit shelters, billboards, and video screens throughout the city.', 649, 2020),
(852, 'Public Art Registry', 'Jayce Salloum&rsquo;s series of works ever close (beyond now) presented on twenty digital screens throughout the city from October 5 to November 1, 2020 with messages that the artist sporadically wrote through his time of quarantine. He describes these messages as &ldquo;sutured manifesto disguised as poetic ramblings and rants out into the void.&rdquo; Trying to present something resonant and useful, his messages tackle our present point of fear, regression, pain, promise and hope, and the unforeseeable future.', 'Two-dimensional artwork', 'Removed', '', '', 'Digital', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/585ab76f1514377146f37ffb18465f8d', 'Privately owned', '', 'Twenty (20) digital sign locations throughout the city', '', 'Platforms 2020: Public Works is a monthly series of temporary public art projects that presented from June 2020 until the end of December 2020.These artworks were selected through an open call inviting Vancouver-based artists to share projects that they have been working on that respond to the circumstances of living during a pandemic and critical time of change.The public art program was launched on transit shelters, billboards, and video screens throughout the city.', 548, 2020),
(853, 'Narratives from the Emptiest Place', 'Rina Lyshaug\'s video Narratives from the Emptiest Place presented on the Vanlive! screen at Robson and Granville (October 5 to November 1, 2020). In this piece, Lyshaug reflects on home as a site for the intervention of the imaginary by presenting an image of a room that challenges the physical boundaries of space.The interjecting video of a quiet home exhibited in an ad-filled environment is a reversal of the usual flow of advertisements, which normally penetrates the domestic site through personal screens. The video simulates time as a projection of sunlight entering the home through a window and moving across an assemblage of walls. The slow pace of the artificial sunlight in the uninhabited space generates a dissonance: a meditative presence embedded within the cacophony of high stimulus messaging emitted by its surrounding advertisements.As a public artwork in Downtown Vancouver, this work takes on a larger cultural significance during the COVID-19 pandemic, when home-confinement is a part of collective experience. The health crisis has relocated shared experiences from crowded bars and sports arenas to isolated homes which are broadcasted as virtual public space through digital communication platforms. This uninhabited room becomes multiple through the eyes of each individual: the act of imaginary projection becomes a form of collective daydreaming.', 'Media work', 'Removed', 'Vanlive! Video Screen', '798 Granville Street', 'Film (no audio)', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/d116446465ba35f88e6b2404c9238f77', 'Privately owned', 'Downtown', 'north-east corner of the Robson and Granville intersection', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.119628, 49.281344]}', 'Platforms 2020: Public Works is a monthly series of temporary public art projects that presented from June 2020 until the end of December 2020.These artworks were selected through an open call inviting Vancouver-based artists to share projects that they have been working on that respond to the circumstances of living during a pandemic and critical time of change.The public art program was launched on transit shelters, billboards, and video screens throughout the city.', 650, 2020),
(855, 'Dobby and the Rest of Us, Distancing', 'Dobby and the Rest of Us, Distancing is a text-based drawing that was created between April 13th and June 5th 2020. It is a collaboration that I made with my seven-year old daughter, Alice. The gift of the covid pandemic is an opportunity to slow down and take the time required to think things through – to make considered works and to spend time with our thoughts in ways we don’t allow for normally. This drawing, which depicts individuals with and without masks on, standing on the landscape (actually a translation of the tundra outside Qamani’tuaq, NU, where my family is from), is constructed out of text and was drawn from left to right. The text begins in the upper right with the date and the number of covid cases worldwide at that moment in time. Its stream of consciousness writing, covers my concerns, preoccupations and thoughts around the pandemic, which eventually simultaneously becomes about the killing of George Floyd and concerns for the continued colonial erasures we enact on Indigenous communities, land and place. In the lower left, when the drawing was finished, the date and number of covid cases appears again thereby making the drawing a unique record of a place and time. The figures, drawn by my young daughter, also reflect her preoccupations during the pandemic. She has carefully planned out the spacing between people (with her best understanding of 2 metres), created a family that stands together in their bubble, and has outfitted several of the figures with masks. She was also particularly obsessed with Harry Potter at the time which is why Dobby makes an appearance.', 'Two-dimensional artwork', 'Removed', '', '370 East Broadway', 'graphite on paper', '', 'City of Vancouver', 'Mount Pleasant', 'Kingsgate Mall lower parking lot located at Broadway and Prince Edward Street', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.097582, 49.262386]}', 'Platforms 2020: Public Works is a monthly series of temporary public art projects that presented from June 2020 until the end of December 2020.These artworks were selected through an open call inviting Vancouver-based artists to share projects that they have been working on that respond to the circumstances of living during a pandemic and critical time of change.The public art program was launched on transit shelters, billboards, and video screens throughout the city.', 0, 2020),
(856, 'Hybrid Creatures', 'Osvaldo Ramirez Castillo&rsquo;s drawing Hybrid Creatures was exhibited on a billboard at Broadway and Prince Edward Street from November 9 to December 7, 2020. Hybrid Creatures proposes the importance of personal myth as a guiding metaphor that supports us to reconnect with our lives. Reflecting on our recent times of collective unease and anxiety, this project offers the public the opportunity to explore and re-discover their own story, voice and myth anew in an uncertain world.', 'Two-dimensional artwork', 'Removed', '', '370 East Broadway', 'Paper poster', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/433b3e0ef1fefd145a64af5e81eb19b8', 'Privately owned', 'Mount Pleasant', 'North east corner of Kingsgate Mall lower parking lot located at Broadway and Prince Edward Street', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.097582, 49.262386]}', 'Platforms 2020: Public Works is a monthly series of temporary public art projects that presented from June 2020 until the end of December 2020.  These artworks were selected through an open call inviting Vancouver-based artists to share projects that they have been working on that respond to the circumstances of living during a pandemic and critical time of change.  The public art program was launched on transit shelters, billboards, and video screens throughout the city.', 654, 2020),
(857, 'Flow Tide', 'The video Flow Tide by Japanese calligraphy artist Kisyuu and dancer Shion Skye Carter presented on the VanLive! Screen at Granville and Robson from November 30 to December 27, 2020.  In this work the artists collaborated for the first time while in isolation during the COVID-19 pandemic to explore the relationship between traditional calligraphy and dance.', 'Media work', 'Removed', 'Vanlive! Video Screen', '798 Granville Street', 'Film (no audio)', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/0b801f56963096bf9d8b7a7d76ffdce0', 'Privately owned', 'Downtown', 'north-east corner of the Robson and Granville intersection', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.119628, 49.281344]}', 'Platforms 2020: Public Works is a monthly series of temporary public art projects that presented from June 2020 until the end of December 2020.  These artworks were selected through an open call inviting Vancouver-based artists to share projects that they have been working on that respond to the circumstances of living during a pandemic and critical time of change.  The public art program was launched on transit shelters, billboards, and video screens throughout the city.', 651, 2020),
(858, 'Placeholder', 'Placeholder  by Ryley O&rsquo;Byrne is a digital and photo collage exhibited on the billboard at Helmcken near Granville (November 9 to December 7, 2020).  Since the pandemic O&#39;Byrne has been working on a project documenting touch, intimacy, and loss through text and images. Interested in how the world has had to shift and expand methods of communicating, the artist captures this curious and complicated space where technology and humanity blend.', 'Two-dimensional artwork', 'Removed', '', '', 'Photography and digital collage', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/65fc325a2b6fd7f6ea3b2799e04e62d9', 'Privately owned', 'Downtown', 'Impark Parking Lot on Helmcken between Granville St and Howe St', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.124837, 49.27861]}', 'Platforms 2020: Public Works is a monthly series of temporary public art projects that presented from June 2020 until the end of December 2020.  These artworks were selected through an open call inviting Vancouver-based artists to share projects that they have been working on that respond to the circumstances of living during a pandemic and critical time of change.  The public art program was launched on transit shelters, billboards, and video screens throughout the city.', 652, 2020),
(859, 'Distant', 'Gerri York&rsquo;s photographic series Distant presented on twenty digital signs throughout the city (November 2 to 29, 2020). This series was shot by the artist as they waited to enter an Antony Gormley exhibition at the Hayward Gallery in London, and documents visitors struggling to negotiate their way through the interior of the gallery. These photographs record an installation intended to solicit disorientation, and are looked to now by York as a chilling reminder of social distancing measures and typical encounters that we have in public space today.', 'Two-dimensional artwork', 'Removed', '', '', 'digital film', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/7e5ff024eaa281fa4168129d50e8df86', 'Privately owned', '', 'Twenty (20) digital sign locations throughout the city', '', 'Platforms 2020: Public Works is a monthly series of temporary public art projects that presented from June 2020 until the end of December 2020.  These artworks were selected through an open call inviting Vancouver-based artists to share projects that they have been working on that respond to the circumstances of living during a pandemic and critical time of change.  The public art program was launched on transit shelters, billboards, and video screens throughout the city.', 653, 2020),
(860, 'Harmoniousness Reductions', 'Manuel Axel Strain&rsquo;s photograph Harmoniousness Reductions presented on twenty transit shelters throughout the city from November 2 to 29, 2020. This work brings greater visibility to the current health crisis that is less talked about: the overdose epidemic, and its disproportionate impact on Indigenous people. The artist describes the work as an image of survival, and testament to their own endurance as having been sober now for over six and a half years and having lost countless others to the disease.', 'Two-dimensional artwork', 'Removed', 'Transit shelters around the city', '', 'Digital photograph printed on paper', '', '', '', '20 Transit Shelter advertisement locations', '', 'Platforms 2020: Public Works is a monthly series of temporary public art projects that presented from June 2020 until the end of December 2020.  These artworks were selected through an open call inviting Vancouver-based artists to share projects that they have been working on that respond to the circumstances of living during a pandemic and critical time of change.  The public art program was launched on transit shelters, billboards, and video screens throughout the city.', 576, 2020),
(861, 'Waiting On A Friend, from the series Isolation', 'The photograph, Waiting on a Friend from the series Isolation by Wade Comer presented on a billboard at Broadway and Prince Edward St from December 7 to January 3, 2020.  In this photograph Comer uses a long exposure to capture Stanley Park at night revealing details that are often obscured during the daytime, and provides an image of an empty bench that is a fitting analogy for a world in lockdown.', 'Two-dimensional artwork', 'In place', '', '370 E Broadway', 'Photograph on vinyl sheeting', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/6de4f8c6b8ff0eb5175b3ed2be86edad', 'Privately owned', 'Mount Pleasant', 'North east corner of Kingsgate Mall lower parking lot located at Broadway and Prince Edward Street', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.097582, 49.262386]}', 'Platforms 2020: Public Works is a monthly series of temporary public art projects that presented from June 2020 until the end of December 2020.  These artworks were selected through an open call inviting Vancouver-based artists to share projects that they have been working on that respond to the circumstances of living during a pandemic and critical time of change.  The public art program was launched on transit shelters, billboards, and video screens throughout the city.', 656, 2020),
(862, 'Dear Tree', 'The drawing and text Dear Tree by the artist Nick Conbere and poet Fred Wah presented on transit shelters throughout the city from November 30 to December 27, 2020.  This collaborative drawing is based on sketches that Conbere created of Vancouver&rsquo;s surrounding forests to which Wah responded through poetry.', 'Two-dimensional artwork', 'Removed', '', '', 'Pencil on paper', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/b7977ecc6a81e77e6fb50d4f0e4b7821', 'Privately owned', '', 'Twenty (20) transit shelter advertisement locations around the city', '', 'Platforms 2020: Public Works is a monthly series of temporary public art projects that presented from June 2020 until the end of December 2020.  These artworks were selected through an open call inviting Vancouver-based artists to share projects that they have been working on that respond to the circumstances of living during a pandemic and critical time of change.  The public art program was launched on transit shelters, billboards, and video screens throughout the city.', 657, 2020),
(863, 'Gaslight', 'Gaslight is a neon sign with the word &ldquo;gaslight&rdquo; written in glowing block letters, circled by the outline of a flickering gas flame. The name is a pun on the nature of neon, as literally light made from gas.  The design of the sign was inspired by the title card for the 1940 film Gaslight. With the film&rsquo;s success, the term &quot;gaslighting&quot; was adopted in psychology to refer to a form of abuse in which the victim is covertly manipulated into doubting their own memory, perception, judgement, and eventually their sanity. More recently this term has been used to describe the manipulation of an entire society through misinformation and destabilizing the concept of truth.   In the current context fractured by a global public health pandemic, the inequalities of late capitalism, the violence of systemic racism, and a looming catastrophic climate crisis, the term &quot;gaslighting&quot; has re-emerged as a powerful signifier and imminent warning of the gap between perception and reality.', 'Site-integrated work', 'In place', 'Del Mar Inn', '555 Hamilton Street', 'White neon', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/49edd1448ed2431cea8b44149093e8be', 'Privately owned', 'Downtown', 'Northeast roofline of the Del Mar Inn', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.112298, 49.281596]}', 'A neon artwork mounted on the roofline of the Del Mar Inn.  Commissioned by Fillip with the support of the City of Vancouver Public Art Program.', 660, 2020),
(864, 'We Are One', 'Tafui&rsquo;s striking work We Are One (2020) presented on a billboard at Helmcken near Granville from December 7, 2020 to January 3, 2021. Tafui&rsquo;s practice includes painting, printmaking, wood carving, and textile art, the interconnectedness between these disciplines explored through a restructuring of approaches to minimal mark-making.  The artist explains: &ldquo;My work is inspired by the idea that &lsquo;we belong to each other&rsquo; and through the understanding of our histories and shared experiences we become united, as people, as cultures, and to the earth.&rdquo;', 'Two-dimensional artwork', 'Removed', '', '', 'mixed media on paper', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/eb245740b61f8622fbf4b4ccf2c9ae0b', 'Privately owned', 'Downtown', 'Impark Parking Lot on Helmcken between Granville St and Howe St', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.124837, 49.27861]}', 'Platforms 2020: Public Works is a monthly series of temporary public art projects that presented from June 2020 until the end of December 2020.  These artworks were selected through an open call inviting Vancouver-based artists to share projects that they have been working on that respond to the circumstances of living during a pandemic and critical time of change.  The public art program was launched on transit shelters, billboards, and video screens throughout the city.', 659, 2020),
(865, 'Weekend Chime', 'Weekend Chime is a sound installation that plays notes based on the chorus of Loverboy&rsquo;s iconic song, Working for the Weekend every Friday at 5 p.m., to signal the end of the traditional work week and the beginning of the weekend. More specifically, the chime sounds the two-note melody used by singer Mike Reno while singing the word &ldquo;weekend&rdquo; in the chorus that gives the song its title. The artwork explores themes of class, labour struggles and the versatility of pop music.  Although the lyrics seem to loosely depict a kind of social-recreational interaction, the artist has interpreted the song as an unofficial sing-along anthem for the weekend itself and for working people. The artist Brady Cranfield says &ldquo;I see a parallel between the way everyday people use, reuse, remake and occupy that space and the way that we use, reuse, remake and occupy pop songs. Weekend Chime will hopefully act as a reminder that we&rsquo;re all workers, the true producers of value in the world.&rdquo;', 'Site-integrated work', 'In place', 'Robson Street Public Plaza', '800 Robson Street', 'Carillon chime system, power amplifier, 4 Atlas speakers, conductor wiring', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/94d11345a4dd95b830637d3a0d251f15', 'City of Vancouver', 'Downtown', 'The artwork\'s four red horns are installed on top of a lighting pole at Robson Street\'s plaza behind the Vancouver Art Gallery.', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.120461, 49.282879]}', 'Weekend Chime was one of five projects commissioned as part of the Public Art Program&#39;s 2017 Artist-Initiated Public Call.', 591, 2021),
(866, 'COEXIST', 'Stills from Mustaali Raj&rsquo;s digital animation COEXIST exhibited on digital street signage throughout the city from November 30 to December 27, 2020.  In these digital stills, Raj presents the resilience of circular forms as they morph into familiar and new forms, creating integrated patterns that are ever-changing.', 'Two-dimensional artwork', 'Removed', '', '', 'digital film', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/7560cc0645e7df6719e52b258b50199b', 'Privately owned', '', 'Twenty (20) digital street sign locations around the city', '', 'Platforms 2020: Public Works is a monthly series of temporary public art projects that presented from June 2020 until the end of December 2020.  These artworks were selected through an open call inviting Vancouver-based artists to share projects that they have been working on that respond to the circumstances of living during a pandemic and critical time of change.  The public art program was launched on transit shelters, billboards, and video screens throughout the city.', 661, 2020),
(867, 'A Constellation of Remediation', 'A Constellation of Remediation was a two-year long public art project that exhibited from November 2018 to 2021 that included the planting of Indigenous remediation gardens on vacant and untended lots on the unceded homelands of the xʷmə&theta;kʷəyə̓m (Musqueam), Sḵwxw&uacute;7mesh (Squamish), and səlilwətaɬ (Tsleil-Waututh) nations.  The artists chose the constellation of sites based on the significant decolonization work near these locations through the work of the Native Education College (NEC), Urban Native Youth Association (UNYA), and the Wild Salmon Caravan residency and Working Group on Indigenous Food Sovereignty.  The artists&rsquo; ongoing conversations with developers, City and Parks staff, and the public were an integral part of the project, a process that built connection while also shifting consciousness and awareness about bioremediation, and land-stewardship.   UNYA Constellation Garden: Southwest corner of Hastings St &amp; Commercial Dr  The artists developed a remediation garden at a former gas station lot and home of an Urban Native Youth Association (UNYA) facility. Indigenous pollinator plants have been planted, creating a field of flowers that will continue to self-pollinate. In partnership with UNYA, the artists also held bioremediation workshops where they invited Indigenous youth to seed the soil and release butterflies on site.  Southwest corner of 5th Ave and Brunswick St  The artists removed invasive species at an over-looked triangular parklet owned by Aragon Properties Ltd a block away from Native Education College where they held workshops with students who made Indigenous wildflower seed bombs.   Strathcona Park fieldhouse, 857 Malkin Ave  Pollinator plants with a relationship to salmon were planted in collaboration with Dawn Morrison and the Wild Salmon Caravan residency and Working Group on Indigenous Food Sovereignty.', 'Socially engaged art', 'Removed', 'UNYA (Hastings & Commercial), 5th Ave & Brunswick St, Strathcona Park', '', 'plants, soil', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/ef825f754ac6f0db87209c0f81683bd6', 'City of Vancouver', 'Grandview-Woodland', '', '', 'A Constellation of Remediation was one of five projects commissioned as part of the Public Art Program&#39;s 2017 Artist-Initiated Public Call.', 446, 2018),
(868, 'Grey Area', 'Paige Gratland&rsquo;s Grey Area presented on transit shelters throughout the city from November 30th to December 27th, 2020.  This photograph of Gratland&#39;s handwoven &quot;web&quot; was created during the early months of the pandemic as a way to process the uncertainty, injustice, grief, and upheaval that  marked our daily lives. The piece embodies the labour and meditative nature of time spent in my studio under lockdown, and is connected to the use of handwoven cloths as shrouds to cover or protect the body in birth, life and death.', 'Two-dimensional artwork', 'Removed', '', '', 'Photograph of handwoven textile (wool)', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/3201f909c6ca8edf3789926fce3813c9', 'Privately owned', '', 'Twenty (20) transit shelter advertisement locations around the city', '', 'Platforms 2020: Public Works is a monthly series of temporary public art projects that presented from June 2020 until the end of December 2020.  These artworks were selected through an open call inviting Vancouver-based artists to share projects that they have been working on that respond to the circumstances of living during a pandemic and critical time of change.  The public art program was launched on transit shelters, billboards, and video screens throughout the city.', 662, 2020),
(869, 'Personnages', 'Nine mosaic figures inset five columns and span the double-height of the outdoor ground level frontage at the Grosvenor Pacific building. Embedded in black mosaic cladding the nine mosaic figural silhouette drawings will be on both faces of the columns. Some figures will be fully viewed from the outside while others will be more visible from the interior of the building. The mosaic figures will be scaled to the full height of each column face. Central to the proposition of these large-scale outdoor drawings is a concern for what I consider to be drawing&rsquo;s most essential quality; the material presence of line. The rich and long tradition of mosaics is its engagement with and consideration for, process, material and line. A material and process based approach means the drawing must not only be responsive to the architecture, but germane to the community and pertinent to the site. These figural, columnar figures will be captured as modern day caryatides. A considered presence, the figures will be defined and be understood by both the present activities and people that surrounds them today as well as from those the past (history of Leslie House). Solitary and reaching, these gentle and quiet giants will be formidable but not intimidating, abstract yet recognizable, subscribers to no other narrative but the one passersby and visitors choose to impose. Personnages will bear the weight of our unremarkable quotidian and our extraordinary shared existence.', 'Site-integrated work', 'In place', 'The Pacific', '889 Pacific Street', 'Glass mosaic tiles (tesserae)', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/536b262d74e87e4d7fb518e81ede5fd9', 'Privately owned', 'Downtown', 'Nine mosaic figures inset five columns and span the double-height of the outdoor ground level frontage of the building', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.13079, 49.27632]}', 'Personnages was commissioned by Grosvenor Americas as part of their participation in the City of Vancouver&#39;s Public Art Program for Private Development.', 563, 2021),
(870, 'Speaker A', 'Speaker A is a permanent sound installation that creates impact with the precise manipulation of directional sound as an auditory, &lsquo;sculptural&rsquo; presence. The work includes three distinct audio tracks, installed at specific locations within the plaza. Specialized directional speakers are integrated into the ceiling panels, producing a highly controlled sound &ldquo;column&rdquo; that visitors walk into and out of at will. Customized paving on the ground plane visually identifies the location of the work.  The audio tracks are a series of collaborative texts/stories, gleaned from fourteen writers from around the city that, when taken together, weave narratives that define lives lived in proximity: restlessness and care. Each speaker reveals a randomized program of short narratives that span past, present and future: the work invites listeners to explore the ideas of Restless Futures (Speaker A), Speculative Pasts (Speaker B) and Instructions for Care in the present (Speaker C). Owing to programming by Remy Siu and responsive sound design by Antoine B&eacute;dard, each speaker retains a constantly shifting presence; each listener experiences a unique sequence of narrative and sound.  The narratives are drawn from emerging and established writers, including Lorna Brown, Lili Robinson, Amber Dawn, Aryo Khakpour, James Long, Maiko Yamamoto, Whess Harman, Amiel Gladstone, Jus-tine A. Chambers, Cease Wyss, Vanessa Kwan, Hiromi Goto, Faith Sparrow-Crawford, and Tim Carlson.  The use of sound relates to the artist team&rsquo;s interest in creating experiences in public space that draw attention to ideas, histories and subjectivities that lie beneath the surface of the city: quite literally the things we can&rsquo;t see. Each sound work is part of a greater narrative, each text building on a compo-sition that cannot be encompassed in one person&rsquo;s experience alone. The work is expected to evolve as a presence at the site over time, to stand as both a record of this place, in this moment&mdash;many of the narratives were written in 2020, in the midst of the onset of the COVID-19 pandemic, and in many ways reflect that unprecedented experience&mdash;while looking forward and back with speculation, anxiety and hope.', 'Site-integrated work', 'In place', '', '180 East 2nd Avenue', '', 'https://opendata.vancouver.ca/api/datasets/1.0/public-art/images/d51ed6d2e4efc7ffe8ad07127066112f', 'Privately owned - Strata', 'Mount Pleasant', 'Three specific locations in the plaza between the entrance on Main Street and the alley courtyard. Positions are indicated by brass letters (A, B and C) set into the concrete flooring.', '{\"type\": \"Point\", \"coordinates\": [-123.101202, 49.268674]}', 'Speaker A was commissioned by Create Urban Development Corporation as part of their participation in the City of Vancouver&#39;s Public Art Program for Private Development.', 345, 2021);
